entry.title: [Extensions][DNR] Fix prefs deletion for delayed installs
entry.content:
In PopulateExtensionInfoPrefs, certain prefs are supposed to be removed

from the extension_dict. This works fine if extension_dict points

directly to the extension's own prefs, but these prefs are not

removed if it points to a dict for delayed install prefs that are

meant to be applied to the extension's own prefs later (since delayed

install prefs are created from scratch).



To fix this, add a removed_prefs list which stores pref keys that

will actually be removed when a delayed installation is completed.



This was found to be the root cause of the DNR bug found below, and

a regression test was added.



Note: While this fix prevents this issue from popping up again, it

cannot fix corrupted/stale prefs with values from a previous version

of the extension that were not cleaned up for a delayed install or

update.



For the kDNRStaticRulesetPref, this was fixed by incrementing the

ruleset format version which forces a re-index which will write the

correct values to prefs.



The extension just needs to call the

declarativeNetRequest.UpdateEnabledStaticRulesets method to correct

the value of the kDNREnabledStaticRulesetIDs pref.

entry.title: Mojo: Represent maps with int64/uint64 keys as Maps in JS/TS
entry.content:
Mojo bindings code decodes maps for JS/TS in 2 different ways:

(1) as object maps (i.e. {[key: KeyType]: ValueType})

(2) as JS Maps (i.e. Map)

This is based on whether the KeyType is marked as

isValidObjectKeyType.



Previously, int64/uint64 had isValidObjectKeyType: true, so maps with

these mojo types as the key were decoded as object maps in JS/TS.

However, int64/uint64 map to the JS BigInt type. Comments in the JS/TS

generators note that BigInts should not be allowed as Object map keys

and the TypeScript compiler throws an error if an object map uses

bigint keys. As a result the generated type for such maps was a JS

Map, creating a runtime/compile time mismatch.



This CL fixes the mismatch by marking int64/uint64 as invalid object

keys so that they will be decoded as JS Maps instead, matching the

runtime behavior to the existing types.

entry.title: Only allow applicable @page properties in computed style.
entry.content:
When PageMarginBoxes are enabled, only allow applicable properties in an

@page context. The list of applicable properties is here:

https://drafts.csswg.org/css-page-3/#page-property-list



I included a few more, highly related properties, e.g. in cases where a

shorthand property is in the list, and new longhands have been added to

specs after this list was created. For instance, we'll allow

background-position-x and background-position-y, since

background-position is in the list (which in turn is part of the

background shorthand).



Also included border-radius properties, and logical properties, such as

padding-inline-start, for instance.



With this change, non-applicable @page properties will no longer be part

of the computed style, and we can revert crrev.com/c/2215323 , which

removed loading of pending resources for @page. We want resources

requested by properties that do apply - such as background-image.

Rename ParameterizedStyleResolverTest NoFetchForAtPage to

FetchForAtPage. The expectation is that the background-image will be

loaded. Add a new NoFetchForAtPage, which uses list-style-image, which

doesn't apply in an @page context.



No behavior changes intended for now. @page computed style is not

web-exposed directly. The only way this can be observed is if it affects

rendering (upcoming CLs).

entry.title: Reland "[OOPIF PDF] Block non-PDF navigation attempts on PDF frames"

This is a reland of commit 6c12e722cd23ab1afdf90f5848c82472490687fa

Original change's description:

> [OOPIF PDF] Block non-PDF navigation attempts on PDF frames

>

> Block navigation attempts on PDF frames that aren't relevant for PDF

> viewer setup by blocking the request in PdfNavigationThrottle. That way,

> compromised renderers won't be able to navigate the PDF frames.

>

> To avoid a dependency violation, PdfNavigationThrottle (which lives in

> //components/pdf) uses a new ShouldCancelPdfFrameNavigation() function

> in PdfStreamDelegate that ChromePdfStreamDelegate (which lives in

> //chrome/browser/pdf) overrides to block these navigations.

>

> This is a re-land of https://crrev.com/1262045. The original version,

> rebased, can be seen in the first patchset. This CL adjusts comments to

> match code that has been updated since, changes how PDF content frame

> navigations are blocked to be more specific, and adds more test

> coverage to cover cases where iframes are attached to the PDF embedder

> frame. This avoids breaking any existing extensions that may inject

> subframes into the PDF DOM tree.

entry.title: [bookmarks] Fix batch upload deleting bookmarks
entry.content:
In particular, there is one calling site to

BookmarkModelView::RemoveAllSyncableNodes() from

components/browser_sync/sync_client_utils.cc that can be exercised on

iOS and is problematic if feature

`syncer::kEnableBookmarkFoldersForAccountStorage` is enabled (or via

chrome://flag#unified-bookmark-model).

BookmarkModelViewUsingLocalOrSyncableNodes::RemoveAllSyncableNodes()

assumed there is a dedicated BookmarkModel instance for local bookmarks,

but this doesn't hold true when the feature is enabled.



The solution is to avoid BookmarkModel::RemoveAllUserBookmarks() and

instead achieve the same effect, but more selectively, by iterating

through syncable permanent folders and removing all their children.

entry.title: Unify form tracking among FormTracker and AutofillAgent
entry.content:
Currently both FormTracker and AutofillAgent keep their own copy of the

last interacted form, and maintain them inconsistently.



- Set/Update:

- AutofillAgent updates its last interacted form on:

- Autofill events

- FormControlChange events (User edits)

- JSValueChange events (update only, not set)



- FormTracker updates its last interacted form on:

- WillSendSubmitEvent (Not clear why)

- FormControlChange events (User edits)

- TrackAutofilledElement (PWM only with special logic)



This is problematic because FormTracker will then never infer

submissions such as XHR_SUCCEEDED or SAME_DOCUMENT_NAVIGATION on

perfect fillings.



- Reset:

- AutofillAgent resets its last interacted form on:

- FormSubmitted event

- ProbablyFormSubmitted event

- InferFormSubmission event

- Reset



- FormTracker resets its last interacted form on:

- TrackAutofilledElement (Before updating)

- DidCommitProvisionalLoad

- WillSendSubmitEvent

- FrameDetached

- FireFormSubmitted

- FireProbablyFormSubmitted

- FireInferredFormSubmiision



This is also problematic since FormTracker doesn't always reset all its

states before updating, meaning that at some point in time it could be

tracking multiple elements as the last interacted element. Note that

AutofillAgent also doesn't reset its states before set/update

operations, but it always updates all or none of its states.



More importantly, this means that in many many cases, what FormTracker

tracks is different from what AutofillAgent does, and the form that

FormTracker infers submission on is different from the form

entry.title: [blink/bindings] Add ZSTD as a compression algorithm for ParkableString
entry.content:
ParkableString defaults to zlib as its compression algorithm. To improve

(de)compression latency, this CL adds ZSTD as a compression algorithnm. Based on

benchmark results at https://github.com/facebook/zstd, this should be both

smaller, and several times faster than zlib. This is confirmed by local

benchmarks on x86_64.



This is gated by a feature flag. However, Chromium currently only include the

decompression side of zstd, and thus this CL adds compression targets as

well. This has a binary cost, which is ~200kiB on ARM32 Android, and ~400kiB on

ARM64. Since ARM32 Android (and Fuchsia) are platforms where binary size is at a

premium, this CL doesn't add the target on these platforms.

entry.title: [sync] Disable data types when related sync policies are lifted
entry.content:
For signed-in non-syncing users with kReplaceSyncPromosWithSignInPromos

enabled, the expected behaviour when SyncDisabled, or

SyncTypesListDisabled is lifted is to have the types that were affected

by the policy toggled off.

This is not the current case, where affected types become enabled after

lifting the policies.



This CL updates the current behaviour to match the expected, by

introducing SyncPrefsPolicyHandler class which disables the affected

types when the policy is active.



The policies, SyncDisabled and SyncTypesListDisabled support "Dynamic

Policy Refresh"; for SyncPrefsPolicyHandler to work as expected in this

case, it observes SyncServiceObserver.



Note: manual testing of policy dynamic changes is not possible using

experiment settings, for iOS, it is only possible using egtests.

a Robolectric test to a device unit test and adjusted to cover new

behavior.

entry.title: win: Use -O3 in optimize_speed
entry.content:
Pass /clang:-O3 after /O2 in the "optimize_speed" config. This increases

the optimization level for targets in this config from -O2 to -O3 on

Windows.



"/O2" means something slightly different for clang-cl than

"-O2" means for clang!



For clang-cl, "/O2" is short for "/Og /Oi /Ot /Oy /Ob2 /GF /Gy".

"/Ot" is "optimize for speed" and means the same as "-O2" for

clang. The other flags turn on things like -ffunction-sections.



Non-clang-cl clang's -O3 isn't exposed in the clang-cl driver.

But we can use the `/clang:` flag to pass it through.



(See TranslateOptArg() in MSVC.cpp and

CLModePassThroughArgList in Driver.cpp in clang/lib/Driver)

Experimenting with `clang-cl /O2 /clang:-O3 -###` also suggests

that this should do the right thing.)



At least at some point in the past, -O3 made a difference on

non-Windows, so maybe it helps on Windows. But maybe now that

we use PGO everywhere, it doesn't help -- and then we can remove

it on all platforms and get rid of the then-pointless

optimize_speed config. Both would be nice outcomes.
